<DOC><DOCNO> AP880308-0013 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0050EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p BC-OklahomaAt-A-Glance     03-08 0210</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Oklahoma At-A-Glance,220</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are the methods for pickingdelegates from Oklahoma to attend the 1988 Democratic andRepublican national conventions this summer.</TEXT><HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: Bruce Babbitt, Michael Dukakis, RichardGephardt, Albert Gore, Gary Hart, Jesse Jackson, Paul Simon   Pledged delegates: 46   Super delegates: 5   Total: 51   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Saturday, April 23 and Saturday, May 14   All of Oklahoma's 46 pledged Democratic National Conventiondelegates will be allocated in proportion to the results of theMarch 8 primary.   Former House Speaker Carl Albert automatically will receive aseat as a delegate as a former party leader.</TEXT><HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: George Bush, Bob Dole, Jack Kemp, PatRobertson, Pete du Pont, Alexander Haig   Delegates: 36   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Thursday, April 7 and Thursday, April 28   Oklahoma Republicans will allocate their national conventiondelegates among presidential candidates based on the results of theprimary.   Eighteen of the state's national convention delegates will bepicked on a winner-take-all basis from the six congressionaldistricts. The remaining 18 delegates at-large are awarded to thecandidate receiving the most votes statewide.</TEXT></DOC>